<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-trig-graphs" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Trigonometric graphs</title>

  <objectives>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <p>
          Recognize and be able to sketch trigonometric graphs.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Use the graphs of trigonometric functions to interpret important information. 
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Determine symmetries of trigonometric functions.  
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Determine amplitude, period, midline and phase shift. 
        </p>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </objectives>
   
  <assemblage>
    <title>Where will this be used in calculus?</title>
    <p>
      Trigonometric functions are used to model a variety of periodic phenomena, and are therefore an important tool in calculus. 
      Graphs can be used to get an overview of a function, or to obtain specific information easily. Some examples are:
    </p>
    <p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <p>
          Finding the area between curves or the volume of certain solids in integral calculus.   
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Use amplitude, period, midline and phase shift of a periodic function to describe and analyze the characterisics of a modeled situation. 
        </p>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </p>
  </assemblage>

  <introduction>
    <p>    
In this section, we discuss the graphs of trigonometric functions, and some properties of their graphs. 
    </p>
  </introduction>

 <subsection xml:id="trignotation"><title>Sinusoidal Graphs and Notation</title>
<p>
  A <term>sinusoidal function</term><idx>Sinusoidal function</idx> is similar to <m>y=\sin x</m> but possibly shifted, stretched, reflected etc.
Below is an example of a graph of a sinusoidal function.
</p>
 <figure>
  <caption>An example of a sinusoidal graph.</caption>
  <title>An example of a sinusoidal graph. REPLACE WITH NEW GRAPH</title>
  <image source="images/trig1sin" width="70%">
      <shortdescription>
          An example of a sinusoidal graph.
        </shortdescription>
  </image>
</figure>
 
<assemblage><title>Notation</title>
    <image source="images/trig1sin" width="70%">
    </image>

  <p>
    The image shows an example of a sinusoidal graph. To describe the graph, we use some specific notation.
    </p>
    <p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <p>
          The <term>midline</term><idx>Midline</idx> is the horizontal line at middle value between the maximum and the minumum values of the graph.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
         The <term>amplitude</term><idx>Amplitude</idx> is the distance between the midline and the maximum value. 
         This is also equal to the distance between the midline and the minimum value
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Sinusoidal functions are <term>periodic</term><idx><h>Periodic function</h></idx>, which means that they repeat after a certain interval. 
          The length of that interval is called the <term>period</term><idx><h>Period of a function</h></idx>. 
          Therefore we can say that the period of a sinusoidal function is the distance between two consequitive maximum points (which is also the same as the distance between two consequitive minimum points). 
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
        We also use <term>phase shift</term><idx><h>Phase shift</h></idx> to describe sinusoidal graphs. 
        The phase shift is the horizontal distance that the graph has been shifted, compared to the "parent function" <m>y=\sin x</m>. 
        </p>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </p>
  </assemblage> 


 
CONTINUE HERE ***********************************************************

https://www.desmos.com/calculator/9plu0ysrlp





 </subsection>
 
 
  <subsection xml:id="triggraphs"><title>The Six Trigonometric Graphs</title>
  <p> The graphs of the trigonometric functions are given below. </p>
  
 <figure>
  <caption>Graph of <m>y=\sin \theta</m></caption>
  <title>Graph of <m>y=\sin \theta</m></title>
  <image source="images/trig1sin" width="70%">
      <shortdescription>
          Graph of <m>y=\sin \theta</m>.
        </shortdescription>
  </image>
</figure>

<figure>
  <caption>Graph of <m>y=\cos \theta</m></caption>
  <title>Graph of <m>y=\cos \theta</m></title>
  <image source="images/trig1cos" width="70%">
      <shortdescription>
          Graph of <m>y=\cos \theta</m>.
        </shortdescription>
  </image>
</figure>

<figure>
  <caption>Graph of <m>y=\tan \theta</m></caption>
  <title>Graph of <m>y=\tan \theta</m></title>
  <image source="images/trig2tan" width="70%">
      <shortdescription>
          Graph of <m>y=\tan \theta</m>.
        </shortdescription>
  </image>
</figure>

<figure>
  <caption>Graph of <m>y=\cot \theta</m></caption>
  <title>Graph of <m>y=\cot \theta</m></title>
  <image source="images/trig2cot" width="70%">
      <shortdescription>
          Graph of <m>y=\cot \theta</m>.
        </shortdescription>
  </image>
</figure>

<figure>
  <caption>Graph of <m>y=\sec \theta</m></caption>
  <title>Graph of <m>y=\sec \theta</m></title>
  <image source="images/trig2sec" width="70%">
      <shortdescription>
          Graph of <m>y=\sec \theta</m>.
        </shortdescription>
  </image>
</figure>

<figure>
  <caption>Graph of <m>y=\csc \theta</m></caption>
  <title>Graph of <m>y=\csc \theta</m></title>
  <image source="images/trig2csc" width="70%">
      <shortdescription>
          Graph of <m>y=\csc \theta</m>.
        </shortdescription>
  </image>
</figure>

  <aside>
    <p>
      <alert> Study tip: </alert>
    </p>
    <p>  
      You should memorize the graphs of <m>y=\sin \theta</m>, <m>y=\cos \theta</m> and <m>y=\tan \theta</m>. A lot of information can be seen quickly in a graph, and for most people it's easier to memorize a graph than a long list of facts. 
    </p>
  </aside>
  
  <p>
  All six trigonometric functions are <term>periodic</term><idx><h>Periodic function</h></idx>, which means that they repeat after a certain interval, called the <term>period</term><idx><h>Period of a function</h></idx>. 
  The periods for the six functions are as follows:  
  </p>
<table><title>Periods of trigonometric functions.</title>
  <tabular halign="center">
    <row header="yes" bottom="minor" >
      <cell>Function</cell>
      <cell>Period</cell>
    </row>
    <row>
      <cell><m>y=\sin x</m></cell>
      <cell><m>2\pi</m></cell>
    </row>
    <row>
      <cell><m>y=\cos x</m></cell>
      <cell><m>2\pi</m></cell>
    </row>
    <row>
      <cell><m>y=\tan x</m></cell>
      <cell><m>\pi</m></cell>
    </row>
    <row>
      <cell><m>y=\cot x</m></cell>
      <cell><m>\pi</m></cell>
    </row>
    <row>
      <cell><m>y=\sec x</m></cell>
      <cell><m>2\pi</m></cell>
    </row>
    <row>
      <cell><m>y=\csc x</m></cell>
      <cell><m>2\pi</m></cell>
    </row>
  </tabular>
</table>
  </subsection>

  <subsection><title>Properties and symmetries</title>
  <p> 
    One benefit of graphs is that a lot of information about a function can be seen quickly. Some examples are seen below.     
  </p>

<aside>
    <p>
      <alert> Study tip: </alert>
    </p>
    <p>  
      Try answering the questions in <xref ref="graph1" /> yourself before looking at the solution. 
    </p>
  </aside>


  <example xml:id="graph1"><title>Properties from graphs</title>
    <statement>
      <p>
      Use the graphs of trigonometric functions to find the following information:
      <nl>
      <li>
        <p>
          (a) <m>\tan 0</m>
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
        (b) All values of <m>x</m> in the interval <m>[-2\pi, 2\pi]</m> where <m>\sin x = 0</m>. 
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
        (c) All values of <m>x</m> in the interval <m>[-2\pi, 2\pi]</m> where <m>\tan x</m> is undefined.
        </p>
      </li>
    </nl>
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
      Looking at the graphs given earlier in this section, we can easily find the information. 
      </p>
      <p>
      (a) <m>\tan 0 = 0</m>, as seen from the graph of <m>y=\tan \theta</m>. 
      </p>
      <p>
      (b) Looking at the graph of <m>y=\sin \theta</m>, we can see that it crosses the <m>x</m>-axis 5 times in the inteval <m>[-2\pi, 2\pi]</m>, at the <m>x</m>-values <m>x=-2\pi, x=-\pi,  x=0, x=\pi</m> and <m>x=2\pi</m>. 
      </p>
     <p>
      (c) Looking at the graph of <m>y=\tan \theta</m>, we can see that it is undefined 4 times in the inteval <m>[-2\pi, 2\pi]</m>, at the <m>x</m>-values <m>x=-\frac{3\pi}{2}, x=-\frac{\pi}{2},  x=\frac{\pi}{2}</m> and <m>x=\frac{3\pi}{2}</m>. 
      </p>
    </solution>
  </example>

  <exercise><title>Properties from graphs - HOMEMADE</title>
  <webwork>
    <pg-code>
      Context("Numeric");

      $a = random(2,9,1);
      $ans1 = Compute("1")->with(
               tolType => 'absolute',
               tolerance => .000000000000000000001,   );
      $ans2 = Compute("0")->with(
               tolType => 'absolute',
               tolerance => .000000000000000000001,   );
      $ans3 = Compute("-pi/2")->with(
               tolType => 'absolute',
               tolerance => .000000000000000000001,   );     
      $ans4 = Compute("3pi/2")->with(
               tolType => 'absolute',
               tolerance => .000000000000000000001,   );           
      $ans5 = str_cmp("DNE");       
    </pg-code>

    <statement>
      <p>Use the graphs of trigonometric functions to find the following information. </p>
        <p>
          (a) <m>\cos 0 = </m> <var name="$ans1" width="6"/>
        </p>
        <p>
        (b) <m>\tan \pi = </m> <var name="$ans2" width="6"/>
        </p>
        <p>
        (c) All values of <m>x</m> in the interval <m>[-2\pi, 2\pi]</m> where <m>\sin x = -1</m>. 
        List your answers from smallest to largest. If there are only three such values (for example) then write `none' in any remaining answer boxes.
          <var name="$ans3" width="6"/> and <var name="$ans4" width="6"/> and <var name="$ans5" width="6"/> and <var name="$ans5" width="6"/>
        </p>
    </statement>
  </webwork>
</exercise>

<p> 
Graphs also illustrate symmetries. For example, <m>y=\sin \theta</m> and <m>y=\tan \theta</m> are odd functions, while <m>y=\cos \theta</m> is an even function.
</p>
<p>
Recall that a function <m>f(x)</m> is an <term>odd function</term><idx><h>Odd function</h></idx> if <m>f(-x)=-f(x)</m> for all <m>x</m> in the domain of <m>f</m>. 
Visually, this means that the graph has 180 degree symmetry about the origin.
</p>
<p>
 Also, <m>f(x)</m> is an <term>even function</term><idx><h>Even function</h></idx> if <m>f(-x)=f(x)</m> for all <m>x</m> in the domain of <m>f</m>. 
 This means that the graph of <m>f</m> has reflective symmetry about the <m>y</m>-axis. 
 </p>
<p>
 Note that the reflective symmetry must be specifically about the <m>y</m>-axis, for the function to be called an even function. 
 Similarly an odd function must have rotational symmetry about the origin, not some other point. 
</p>

     <example xml:id="graph2"><title>Symmetries - UPDATED PLEASE REVIEW</title>
    <statement>
      <p>
      Which of the following statements are true, and which are false? 
      </p>
      <p>
      <nl>
      <li>
        <p>
          (a) <m>y=\tan x</m> is an odd function. 
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          (b) <m>y=\sec x</m> is an odd function. 
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
        (c) <m>\sin \left(\frac{3}{8}\right) = - \sin \left(-\frac{3}{8}\right)</m>
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
        (d) <m>y=\cos (x-1)</m> is an even function. 
        </p>
      </li>
    
    </nl>
      </p>
    </statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        (a) True
      </p>
      <p>
        (b) False
      </p>      
      <p>
        (c) True
      </p>  
      <p>
        (c) False
      </p>     
    </answer>
    <solution>
       <p>
        (a) This is true. Looking at the graph we see that it is symmetric about the origin. 
      </p>
      <p>
        (b) This is false. Looking at the graph we see that it is symmetric about the <m>y</m>-axis, so <m>y=\sec x</m> is an even function, not odd. 
      </p>      
      <p>
        (c) This is true. This is a property of odd functions and <m>y=\sin x </m> is an odd function. 
      </p> 
      <p>
        (c) This is false. 
        We know that <m>y=\cos x</m> is an even function, but <m>y=\cos (x-1)</m> is shifted 1 unit to the right, so the symmetry is no longer about the <m>y</m>-axis.  
         The function <m>y=\cos (x-1)</m> is not even and not odd.
      </p>    
    </solution>
  </example>

<exercise><title>Symmetries and properties from graphs - HOMEMADE - UPDATED PLEASE REVIEW</title>
  <webwork>
    <pg-code>
      Context("Numeric");

      $a = random(2,9,1);
      $popuptrue = PopUp(['?','True','False'],1);
      $popupfalse = PopUp(['?','True','False'],1);
    </pg-code>

    <statement>
      <p>
        Which of the following statements are true, and which are false? 
      </p>
      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>y=2+ \sin x</m> is an odd function. <var name="$popupfalse" form="popup"/>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>y=\csc x</m> is an odd function. <var name="$popuptrue" form="popup"/>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>\sec \left( 3 \right) = \tan \left( -3 \right)\csc\left(-3\right)</m>  <var name="$popuptrue" form="popup"/>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>\tan \left( \frac{3\pi}{7} \right) = -\tan \left( -\frac{3\pi}{7} \right)</m> <var name="$popuptrue" form="popup"/>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>y=\sec (x-\frac{\pi}{3})</m> is an even function. <var name="$popupfalse" form="popup"/>
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>

    </statement>
  </webwork>
</exercise>
  </subsection>

  <subsection><title>Transformations of graphs</title>
  <p> 
    Transformations of graphs in general may be reviewed in another section. Here we discuss some transformations specifically in terms of trigonometric functions. 
  </p>

    <example xml:id="trans1">
    <title>Basic transformations</title>
    <statement>
      <p>
      Use a graphing tool (for example DESMOS) to graph <m>y=2\cos x</m> and <m>y=\cos (2x)</m>. How are each of them different from the graph of <m>y=\cos x</m>?
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
Let's start by looking at the graphs of <m>y=2\cos x</m> and <m>y=\cos x</m> together. 
      </p>
  <image source="images/trig2ex1" width="70%">
      <shortdescription>
          The graphs of <m>y=2\cos x</m> and <m>y=\cos x</m>.
        </shortdescription>
  </image>

      <p>
      Looking at the graph of <m>y=2\cos x</m>, we see that it looks very similar to the graph of <m>y=\cos x</m>, except that the <m>y</m>-values range between -2 and 2, instead of -1 and 1. The graph of <m>y=2\cos x</m> is streched vertically by a factor of 2, compared to the graph of <m>y=\cos x</m>. This is because all outputs are multiplied by 2 (compared to the corrsponding outputs of <m>y=\cos x</m>). 
      </p>

         <p>
Now let's compare the graphs of <m>y=\cos (2x)</m> and <m>y=\cos x</m>: 
      </p>   
  <image source="images/trig2ex2" width="70%">
      <shortdescription>
          The graphs of <m>y=\cos (2x)</m> and <m>y=\cos x</m>.
        </shortdescription>
  </image>
      <p>
      Looking at the graph of <m>y=\cos (2x)</m>, we see that it again looks similar to the graph of <m>y=\cos x</m>, except its period is <m>\pi</m> instead of <m>2\pi</m>. The oscillations occur `twice as fast' compared to the graph of <m>y=\cos x</m>. The graph of <m>y=\cos (2x)</m> is compressed horizontally by a factor of 2, compared to the graph of <m>y=\cos x</m>.
      </p>
    </solution>
  </example>

<p>
Generalizing what we saw in <xref ref="trans1"/>, the graph of <m>y=A \cos x</m>  (for <m>A \not= 0)</m> oscillates between <m>A</m> and <m>-A</m> (because it has been stretched vertically). 
Similarly for the graph of <m>y=A \sin x</m>. 
Therefore, <m>A</m> is the amplitude of the sine or cosine curve. 
</p>
<p>
The graphs of <m>y=\cos (kx)</m> and <m>y=\sin (kx)</m>  (for <m>k \not= 0</m>) have periods of <m>2\pi /k</m>. 
This is because compared to <m>y=\cos x</m> and <m>y=\sin x</m>, the graphs of <m>y=\cos (kx)</m> and <m>y=\sin (kx)</m> are compressed horizontally by a factor of <m>k</m>.
</p>

<p>
Compared to <m>y=\cos x</m>, the graph of <m>y=\cos (x+c)</m> is shifted <m>c</m> units left if <m>c > 0</m> and right if <m>c</m> is less than 0. 
Here, <m>c</m> is called the <term>phase shift</term><idx><h>Phase shift</h></idx> or <term>horizontal translation</term><idx><h>Horizontal translation</h></idx> or sometimes horizontal shift. 
However, the term ``horizontal translation'' applies to any graphs translated horizontally, while the term ``phase shift'' is used only for sinusoidal graphs.
</p>

     <example xml:id="graph3"><title>Amplitude, period, phase shift</title>
    <statement>
      <p>
      Find the amplitude, period and phase shift for the curve
      <me>
        y = 3 \sin (4x-7)
      </me>
      </p>
    </statement>
    <answer>
        <p>
          The amplitude is <m>3</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          The period is <m>\frac{\pi}{2}</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          The phase shift is <m>\frac{7}{4}</m>.
        </p>
    </answer>
    <solution>
       <p>
        The amplitude is given by the constant multiplied by <m>\sin \theta</m>, in this case 3. 
       </p>
<p>
  To find the period, notice that compared to <m>y=\sin x</m>, the graph of <m>y = 3 \sin (4x-7)</m> is compressed by a factor of <m>4</m>. This means the period is divided by <m>4</m>. The period of <m>y=\sin x</m> is <m>2\pi</m>, which means the persiod of <m>y = 3 \sin (4x-7)</m> is <m>\frac{2\pi}{4}= \frac{\pi}{2}</m>.
</p>

<p>
  To find the phase shift, we need to consider <m>(4x-7)</m>. It is easier to see the phase shift if we first factor the <m>4</m>:
  <me>
    y = 3 \sin (4x-7) =  3 \sin \left(4\left(x-\frac{7}{4}\right)\right)
  </me>
  Now we see that the curve has been shifted <m>\frac{7}{4}</m> units to the right, so the phase shift is <m>\frac{7}{4}</m>. 
</p>
    </solution>
  </example>

  <exercise><title>Determining period - HOMEMADE</title>
  <webwork>
    <pg-code>
      Context("Numeric");

      $a = random(2,9,1);
      $ans1 = Compute("pi/$a")->with(
               tolType => 'absolute',
               tolerance => .000000000000000000001,   );

    </pg-code>

    <statement>
      <p>
        Compared to the graph of <m>y=\tan x</m>, the graph of <m>y=\tan (<var name="$a"/>x)</m> is compressed horizontally by a factor of <m><var name="$a"/></m>. 
      </p>
      <p> 
        What is the period of <m> \tan \left(<var name="$a"/>x\right)</m>? <var name="$ans1" width="6"/>
      </p>
    </statement>
  </webwork>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="ex-trig-graph1"><title>Amplitude, period, phase shift from graph - WEBWORK</title>
